{{About|the historian|the chemist|Dorothy Marshall}}
'''Dorothy Marshall''' (26 March 1900 &ndash; 13 February 1994) was an English social historian.<ref name="Times">''The Times'' (17 February 1994), p. 19.</ref> She was educated at [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] grammar school and [[Girton College, Cambridge|Girton College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], where her tutor was [[Eileen Power]].<ref name="Times" /> She did postgraduate research at the [[London School of Economics]] and in 1926 her PhD was published as ''The English Poor in the Eighteenth Century''.<ref name="Times" /> Marshall worked at [[Bedford College, London|Bedford College]], [[University of Durham|Durham University]] and finally [[University of Cardiff|Cardiff University]], where one of her pupils was [[Roy Jenkins]].<ref name="Times" />
==Works== *''The English Poor in the Eighteenth Century'' (London: George Routledge & Sons, 1926). *''English People in the Eighteenth Century'' (London: Longmans, Green & Co., 1956). *''Eighteenth Century England'' (London: Longmans, Green & Co., 1962).
