{{for|the Dean of Clogher|Richard Bagwell (priest)}} '''Richard Bagwell''' (9 December 1840 – 4 December 1918) was a noted historian of the [[House of Stuart|Stuart]] and [[Tudor dynasty|Tudor]] periods in Ireland, and a political commentator with strong [[Unionism in Ireland|Unionist]] convictions. He was the eldest son of [[John Bagwell (1811-1883)|John Bagwell]], M.P. for [[Clonmel (UK Parliament constituency)|Clonmel]] from 1857 to 1874. His son [[John Philip Bagwell]] followed the family tradition in politics becoming a [[Seanad Éireann|Senator]] in the government of the [[Irish Free State]] in 1923.
== Academic career == Bagwell was educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and [[Oxford University|Oxford]] in England and [[Call to the Bar|called to the Bar]], being admitted to [[Inner Temple]] in 1866. He was the author of ''Ireland Under the Tudors'' (1885-1890) and ''Ireland Under the Stuarts'', 3 vols. (1909–10), in recognition for which he was given the honorary degree of [[Doctor of Letters|Litt. D.]] by [[Trinity College, Dublin|Dublin University]] in 1913 and that of D.Litt. by Oxford University in 1917. He also wrote the historical entry on ‘Ireland’ for the [[Encyclopædia Britannica]] (Chicago 1911).<ref>[http://www.ricorso.net/rx/az-data/index.htm Ricorso]</ref>
== Politics == Bagwell was a Commissioner on National Education between 1905 and 1918 and a member of the Patriotic Union (Southern Unionists).<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FKX/is_3-4_38/ai_111265621/pg_26 ''Landlord responses to the Irish Land War, 1879-87''] Éire-Ireland:Journal of Irish Studies, at BNet</ref> He held the position of [[High Sheriff of Tipperary|High Sheriff of County Tipperary]] in 1869. He was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for [[County Tipperary]] (and later for [[County Waterford|Waterford]]), and held the office of [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of Tipperary. He was also Special Local Government Commissioner between 1898 and 1903<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p26513.htm#i265122 Richard Bagwell at ThePeerage.Com]</ref> and President of the Borstal Association of Ireland.
== Personal life == Bagwell married [[Harriet Bagwell|Harriet Philippa Joscelyn]] (née Newton) on 9 January 1873. The couple had one son, [[John Philip Bagwell]], and three daughters, Emily Georgiana, Margaret and [[Lilla Minnie Perry|Lilla Minnie]]. He died 4 December 1918 at Marlfield.<ref name=Dempsey>{{cite book|last1=Dempsey |first1=Pauric J.|last2=White|first2=Lawrence William|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=Dictionary of Irish Biography|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=Bagwell, Richard}}</ref>
